{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Use South African English|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox cricketer | name = Don MacLeod | image = | caption = | batting = Right-hand bat | bowling = Right-arm medium | columns = 1 | column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]] | matches1 = 4 | runs1 = 57 | bat avg1 = 11.40 | 100s/50s1 = 0/0 | top score1 = 18 | wickets1 = 9 | bowl avg1 = 20.66 | fivefor1 = 0 | tenfor1 = 0 | deliveries1 = 492 | best bowling1 = 3/42 | catches/stumpings1= 1/- | international = false | source = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/46283.html ESPNcricinfo] | date = }}
'''Donald George (Don) MacLeod''' (2 March 1947 in [[Pietermaritzburg]], [[KwaZulu-Natal Province|Natal]]) was a [[South Africa]]n [[cricket]]er who played in four [[First-class cricket|First-class]] matches from 1967 to 1971 and who subsequently played a leading role in the South African sugar industry.
A right-arm medium and right-hand bat, MacLeod played all his [[first class cricket|first class]] matches for the [[Natal cricket team|Natal B]] team, taking 9 wickets and scoring 57 runs. His first match was in January 1968 against the [[Orange Free State cricket team|Orange Free State]] and his subsequent matches during the holiday period (18 December to 18 January) of the 1970/71 season.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://stats.thecricketer.com/Players/14/14000/14000.html |title = Donald MacLeod |publisher = Thecricketer |accessdate = 20 June 2012 }}</ref><ref name="CricInfo profile">{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/46283.html|title=Player Profile: DG MacLeod|publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref>
He became president of the Natal Cricket Union (1991–92) and an executive member of the [[Cricket South Africa|South African Cricket Union]] (1987–90) and after its merger with the [[Cricket South Africa|South African Cricket Board]] of the [[Cricket South Africa|United Cricket Board of South Africa]] (1991–94).<ref name=ww>{{cite web |url = http://www.whoswhosa.co.za/donald-macleod-1199 |title = Donald MacLeod |work = Who's who South Africa |accessdate = 20 June 2012 }}</ref>
After completing degrees at the Universities of [[University of Natal|Natal]] and [[Oxford University|Oxford]], he pursued a management role in the sugar industry, becoming managing director of [[Illovo Sugar]] in 1992 and chairman of the board in 2012. He was also chairman of the South African Sugar Millers Association Limited from 1995 to 1997.<ref name=ww /> During his tenure as managing director, he negotiated the May 1997 R1.6 billion ($225 million, £128 million) deal to merge [[Lonhro]]'s sugar interests with those of Illovo, making Illovo the largest sugar producer in Africa.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://secure.financialmail.co.za/97/0516/invest/illovo.htm |title = Illovo – Full steam ahead into southern Africa |newspaper = Financial Mail [South Africa] |date = 16 May 1997 |accessdate = 20 June 2012 }}</ref>
