'''INFOTAB''' (International Tobacco Information Center) was based in Brussels as the cigarette industry's international lobby organisation.  It developed through four main stages.

Initially the program to set up a joint lobby by the competing cigarette manufacturers was known by the code-name [[Operation Berkshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.library.ucsf.edu/tid/foz1aa00/pdf|title=Industry Documents Library|website=legacy.library.ucsf.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.library.ucsf.edu/tid/vix66b00/pdf|title=Industry Documents Library|website=legacy.library.ucsf.edu}}</ref>  It was formally set up in mid 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.library.ucsf.edu/tid/cyg85a00/pdf|title=Industry Documents Library|website=legacy.library.ucsf.edu}}</ref>

The first actual organisation with staff was established by [[Mary Covington]] on loan from Philip Morris.  It functioned under the name ICOSI (International Committee on Smoking Issues),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu/tobacco/docs/ppdl0012|title=Industry Documents Library|website=www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu}}</ref> and its main operating subcommitte was SAWP (Social Acceptability Working Party) which tried to find ways to make smoking more acceptable to non-smokers. An Australian ex-member of parliament, [[Julian Doyle]] was the main director at this stage.

ICOSI was transformed into INFOTAB in 1984 when they decided to fund and staff the organisation to attack the growing political moves against the tobacco industry with the European Community (based in Brussels), and the World Health Organisation (WHO) and International Labor Organisation (ILO) in Geneva. The WHO in particular had a highly active anti-smoking program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu/tobacco/docs/tmnk0196|title=Industry Documents Library|website=www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu}}</ref> The main director of INFOTAB was the Australian newspaper executive Bryan C Simpson.

In the November 1998, the [[Master Settlement Agreement]] was signed between the Clinton Administration, the US States Attorneys General. and the tobacco industry. This agreement supposedly clamped down  on the underhand activities of the tobacco industry and so INFOTAB was supposed to disappear.  It didn't.

Many of the functions were simply passed over to the Tobacco Documentation Center which was by then a highly diffuse organisation with database operations in various countries, but based initially on the Brussels INFOTAB database division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu/tobacco/docs/stfd0204|title=Industry Documents Library|website=www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.library.ucsf.edu/tid/pfe51a99/pdf|title=Industry Documents Library|website=legacy.library.ucsf.edu}}</ref>

